# Engineering methodology (condensed)

Applies to any non-trivial change — anything beyond a one-file, fully-understood edit. Priority when guidance conflicts: user's explicit instructions > this methodology > built-in defaults. For each matching rule below, read `skills/<slug>/SKILL.md` for the full rules, red-flags, and examples. For non-trivial work, follow the relevant process skill BEFORE writing implementation code — never back-fill the process.

## Rules — one line per skill

- **spec-driven-development** — For a non-trivial feature, write the design chain first: BRIEF → RESEARCH → SPECS (the *what*) → DESIGN (the *how*) → TASKS, each phase consuming the last. Keep *what* and *how* in separate docs. Gate each phase behind a review recorded in the doc. When code diverges, reconcile the spec onto shipped reality and bump its version; strike through resolved items, don't delete them.
- **environment-research** — Before a spec or plan depends on a dependency's real behavior, state a precise hypothesis (execution/outcome/error/boundary modes), write the smallest experiment that could falsify it, and run it against the real thing. Provoke failure modes on purpose. Record what you saw, not what you expected — when the observation contradicts the docs, design against the observation.
- **adversarial-lens-review** — An author cannot grade their own work. At each phase gate, dispatch a fresh reviewer per binding named lens (spec: factual-grounding/completeness/design-flaw/testability; plan: spec-coverage/testing-trackability/sequencing-anti-hubris; implementation: spec-compliance then code-quality) instructed to enumerate, not fix. Require severity-graded findings, loop until BLOCKER/MAJOR clears, and keep the reviewer's context separate from the author's.
- **hexagonal-with-enforced-contracts** — Isolate a framework-free domain that talks only to ports (abstract interfaces); every external system (LLM, DB, cloud SDK, HTTP API) is an adapter implementing a port, and the domain imports no vendor SDK. Enforce the boundary with a machine (import-linter / layering rule / architecture test) that fails the build when domain code reaches for an adapter.
- **configuration-single-source-of-truth** — Collapse any value duplicated across build files, scripts, docs, and code (project id, model name, threshold, rubric, region) to one authoritative source; read it once and pass it down, never re-declare. "What value is in effect?" must have exactly one answer.
- **dev-environment-facade** — Give the dev workflow one surface: a self-documenting Makefile of one-liner recipes delegating to real scripts, gate commands mirrored character-identically (grep-checked). Targets come from the shared cross-repo vocabulary (universal `help`/`setup`/`test`/`check`/`clean`/`dod`; family verbs, none without its capability, required exactly when it fires unless the manifest role says optional or mutating: `stack-start/stop/status/destroy`, open `test-<tier>` — bare tier names never, `build`, `lint`/`fix`/`audit`/`sast`/`hooks`, `docs`/`docs-serve`, `clean-all`; full list in the skill's `vocabulary.txt`, reference checker beside it); project-specific names stay free, never rebinding a standard name or reserved prefix, and no aliases; a shared name keeps one promise in every repo, `check` never certifies less than the read-only quality leaves whose capability fires + unit suite + docs build where docs exist, and a backend's verb is borrowed only while the target delivers at least the verb's home meaning and destroys nothing that meaning leaves intact. Split env files by owner — provisioning writes the machine file (atomic, conditional mint against a probed discriminating endpoint); no script ever writes the user file. Tests load env in-process at fixture time, shell wins with a shadow warning; absent file skips, present-but-broken hard-fails.
- **surgical-changes-with-checkpoints** — Change exactly what the task requires and nothing more; match surrounding conventions; note unrelated improvements separately. Before risky work (migrations, dep bumps, refactors, infra), create a known-good fallback first (checkpoint commit, stash, throwaway branch, tagged snapshot). Split commits by reason with a conventional type prefix; write each as a decision record — what, why, and the evidence that proves it correct.
- **additive-default-off-feature-flags** — Ship new capability additively, behind a flag or as an optional collaborator, so the default path stays the prior proven behavior. New code is inert until something explicitly opts in (env flag, config toggle, injected non-default impl, optional dependency). Roll forward and back by flipping a switch, not reverting code.
- **battle-testing-on-real-infra** — Before calling any integration, deployment, or guarantee "done," prove it end-to-end against the real systems (live API, real DB, deployed runtime) and save a named evidence artifact someone else can open (results file, captured log, saved response). Mocks prove wiring, not external reality. Treat the spec as a hypothesis and the running system as ground truth, recording each divergence in the code. When a path needs infra you lack, drive the real route and assert its exact semantic rejection rather than dropping to mocks; mark a path untested only when even that is impossible, and name what's missing. For a model-backed feature, round-trip a real local model, not a mock.
- **acceptance-tests-observable-outcomes** — Completion is what a user or caller observes, not which code paths ran: for each observable success criterion, write an executable acceptance test against the real system, derived from the spec before or independent of the implementation. Assert semantic essentials, not incidental formatting. Run teardown unconditionally. Treat a red or missing acceptance test as the real "not done yet" signal, not a green unit suite.
- **grounded-verifiable-gates** — Convert fuzzy LLM/agent output into a verifiable signal: define grounding invariants (every claim cites a real source span; every cited id exists), a deterministic gate that yields pass/fail or a score, and a CI-able eval harness that runs the gate over a fixed corpus on every change. Trust the gate's verdict, never raw model output.
- **definition-of-done-tooling** — The author never self-certifies "done" — a script does. Declare every completion criterion as `required` or `n/a` in a small config, back every required line with a real check, and run them through one gate that emits a single GO/NO-GO. Mark `n/a` visibly, never delete silently; fix and re-run on NO-GO, never edit the config to pass.
- **honest-reframing-over-overclaiming** — When a live result contradicts the hoped-for story, rewrite the claim to match the measurement (carry the exact numbers) — never bend tests, fixtures, thresholds, or labels to manufacture a pass. Propagate every correction to every artifact it appeared in. Never touch ground truth to win; if a fixture seems to need changing, stop and get explicit agreement. Keep a balanced corpus of good and bad cases. Defer honestly, naming the exact missing precondition.
- **evidence-over-deference** — When a request rests on a premise you can check in seconds, check it first. If the evidence contradicts the premise or the request conflicts with a recorded principle, say so once — the finding, its source, a concrete alternative — before executing. When the human proposes a direction, weigh the strongest real alternative yourself before taking a stance — mirrored agreement and manufactured pushback both carry no information. The human's decision wins after being heard: execute fully, record consequential dissent, don't relitigate without new evidence. Symmetric: surface your own uncertainty; concede on evidence, not on pressure.
- **reversible-by-default-confirm-consequential** — Keep agents and automation read-only or reversible by default; gate consequential, hard-to-undo actions (writing to a system of record, sending a message, deleting data, spending money, mutating prod) behind a durable human-approval pause the human can inspect, approve, or reject — not a fire-and-forget prompt. Default to dry-run/preview; require an explicit, logged confirmation to cross into irreversible territory.
- **structural-security-boundary** — When untrusted or agent-generated code executes, put the real trust boundary in a layer the actor cannot reach (a separate UID, a read-only mount, dropped capabilities, a VM); a shared-kernel container only reduces blast radius, it does not fully contain. Pattern/command guards are labelled defense-in-depth that *fail toward asking*, never the boundary — prefer an allow-list fast-path plus deny-by-default, and deny on absent or ambiguous input. Grant least privilege and let a machine enforce the seam. When you can't reach the structural bar yet, name the residual exactly and pin it as a passing-by-design test; never self-certify a trust-boundary change.
- **secrets-and-teardown-discipline** — Make secrets structurally un-committable (gitignored secret files, env injection, a secret manager — never a literal in source or history); grant least privilege; always tear down what you stood up, then verify zero remains rather than assuming it. Own only your scope — don't delete shared or pre-existing resources you didn't create.
- **docs-as-deliverable** — Treat docs as first-class as code: tight present-tense prose stating what the system *does*, not what it might do; diagrams authored as code over screenshots that rot; every claim verified against running reality; validated by a real reader who can follow it without you in the room.
- **decision-memory** — Capture a decision, gotcha, or preference at the moment of discovery as a small, dated, indexed note (what was decided/learned, and why), linked from an index, not buried in prose. Before trusting an existing note, verify it still holds — stale memory confidently asserted is worse than none.
- **autonomous-self-improvement-loop-safety** — When automation acts on its own substrate (an agent that edits, tests, or deploys its own repo), run each cycle in a disposable, freshly-cloned workspace and destroy it after; decide success by a *mechanical* version-control check, never the worker's own "done"; bind tested==shipped so the revision that passed the gate is the one that ships; keep a recurring adversarial self-review that assumes the gate is blind; stay propose-only with a human (or a credential that structurally cannot merge) on the landing; sandbox the write-capable worker structurally, not by prompt. Label every step real or mock and fail closed on mock.
- **parallel-agent-fan-out** — When you fan out many write-capable sub-agents across one build (N modules, endpoints, call-sites), design the independence in and trust no report out: pre-wire the shared seams (registry, stubs, fixtures) so each agent fills only a leaf; give each a disjoint file-ownership manifest and revert violations; on shared live substrate namespace every resource an agent creates and forbid it touching anything it didn't create, cleaning up in a finalizer; re-run each agent's own gate yourself (tests, types, lint, live run) against the merged tree, believing the exit code not the prose; serialize the join so only the coordinator edits shared seams. Cut along real independence — if two units must edit the same file, they are one unit.

